I am an avid fan of sweetgreen and often go to the one close to my apartment. I always get a delicious salad and staff is friendly. Thus, I recommended to my friend to try sweetgreen. We went to the one in Foggy Bottom and I can honestly say I have never dealt with such mean employees. My friend, not knowing the menu, asked to make a substitution, and instead of someone explaining to her that it would cost more money or she could not, they yelled at her and patronized her until she was on the verge of tears, she eventually got to the front and they asked her if she wanted bread where she said no. They asked again saying "you sure? you look like you want some bread," several times and she continued to say no. Even after saying no, they put it in anyway. As someone who has worked in food service, I have never seen such disregard for a customer. By the time we left, my friend was on the verge of tears and said she was actually scared to go to another sweetgreen. Needless to say, I have lost respect for this location.

It's a bit on the pricy side, but Sweetgreen is my go to lunch spot.  With all the buzz around Whole Foods - just 30m away - I find the food at Sweetgreen to be of much higher quality.  They're lacking a few critical things – like WiFi and coffee – that prevent me from going there more often.  I'd love to go there in the evenings when business is slow to work on my laptop, but WiFi is currently not available.  Whether you're an adherent to the locavore movement or not, the rotation of ingredients at Sweetgreen is very much appreciated.

Sweetgreen is definitely worth a visit. I usually get the salads in wrap form, which makes them feel less intimidating. I don't know why...  I wish that their August salad would be a permanent addition: arugala base, mint, cantaloupe, feta cheese, a shot of sriracha, and some lemon-tahini hummus (I think I added the last part myself)  I liked it so much that I tried to recreate it at home with my panini maker. So good...

This fast food style restaurant allows you to make custom salads or pick from some premade options. The price is very reasonable for the quality of food that they serve. The employees are also very efficient; if you know what you want, you can have your salad ready in under a minute. They have seating in the restaurant or you can get your food to go, so it is perfect both for a quick meal or sit-down dining.  Sweetgreen is also very committed to its sustainability; they laud their numerous organic and local food options, including organic frozen yogurt. Because it is a salad restaurant, there are plenty of vegan and vegetarian options, especially because you can customize your salad. They also compost their food; they compost their food scraps behind the counter and have a composting trashcan available for customers to sort their trash. Even their containers and cutlery are biodegradable. They use LED and fluorescent lighting and offset all their energy with wind energy credits. All in all, Sweetgreen is a company dedicated to sustainability with food well worth the price.

Overall, I think this place is fantastic for a quick salad joint.  Their salads are usually very fresh and well prepared.  However, today I tried gazpacho and a salad with shrimp.  The gazpacho seemed to be swimming in citric acid, and the shrimp tasted as if they had been treated chemically.  Perhaps the ingredients were fine and my taste buds were just "off" today.  However, I typically eat preservative-free, all-natural foods, so I've become pretty good at detecting when preservatives are included.  MOST of Sweet Green's food is great, but my advice: stay away from the shrimp.
